== Hardened Kernels ==

The upstream Kernel Self Protection Project<ref>http://www.openwall.com/lists/kernel-hardening</ref> (KSPP) was established in 2015 with the goal of introducing more hardening features into mainline Linux. This includes many features found in the Grsecurity patchset, which was publicly available until early 2017. One advantage of KSPP is that users will no longer need to compile and tweak settings to create a secure kernel, as many hardening features become the default over time in various distributions. Up-to-date information on available hardening features can be viewed [https://github.com/a13xp0p0v/linux-kernel-defence-map here].

The Hardened Kernel Project is a collaborative effort between Arch and Gentoo developers who handled Grsecurity packaging in their respective distributions with the goal of accelerating mainlining of the patchset. <ref>https://wiki.gentoo.org/wiki/Hardened/Hardened_Kernel_Project</ref><ref>https://github.com/thestinger/linux-hardened</ref>

While kernel hardening is important, it only addresses a subset of security risks. It cannot protect against backdoors or security issues related to design, policy or yet unknown exploit classes.

